Bye-bye to accident in new operation Tsuruoka Station works with related organizations to raise safety awareness|Yamagata Newspaper
At the bicycle class held as the start of the operation, a collision test between a car and a bicycle was conducted = Shoko Gakuen Automobile School, Tsuruoka City
In recent years, Tsuruoka Police Station (Chief Sato Keizo) has launched "Operation Zero Buy-by Accidents" in an effort to eliminate accidents involving bicycles and motorcycles, which occur at a high rate within the jurisdiction.
In addition to raising awareness of accident prevention together with traffic safety organizations within their jurisdiction, they will also strengthen the crackdown on violations of traffic rules on bicycles.
This year, three traffic fatal accidents occurred within the department's jurisdiction, killing a person who was driving a motorcycle or bicycle.
Although the number of accidents has been on a declining trend, as of June 30th, accidents involving bicycles accounted for about 11.7%, and motorcycles accounted for about 5.8%, all of which are higher than the prefectural average.
In particular, the incidence of bicycle accidents over the past five years has exceeded the prefectural average, and a strategy was planned to overcome this situation.
The name of the operation multiplied "bike" and "bicycle" with the meaning of eradicating accidents.
Affiliated organizations will be called on to provide driving guidance to the elderly and make use of nightlight reflective materials at traffic safety classes more than ever before.
In the event of a crackdown, the department will issue a yellow card (guidance warning form) to encourage caution.
The opening ceremony for the operation was held on the 21st at the Shoko Gakuen Automobile School in Tsuruoka.
Approximately 30 people involved were in attendance, and Chief Sato said, "We would like to ask for your cooperation to reduce tragic accidents as much as possible."
A person in charge of the department presented the policy and the activities of each organization.
A bicycle class will continue to be held as the start of the operation.
They demonstrated how the impact on a bicycle differs between a police officer in a car applying a brake and colliding with a bicycle, and a collision at a speed of about 55 km/h without stepping on the brake.
Kanai Koichi, chairman of the Tsuruoka District Regional Traffic Safety Activity Promotion Committee, said, "I realized once again the horror of traffic accidents. I would like to call attention not only to the elderly but also to young people."
