I want to know as soon as possible where and what kind of disasters and accidents occurred! '
There is a strong need not only for the press such as television and newspapers, but also for many companies such as social infrastructure companies and local governments.
A service that responds to this is "Spectee" developed by Spectee, a company that analyzes information using AI.
Photo: A specialist team determines the authenticity of social media information through alerts from Specti
Today, the first way for people to learn about the occurrence of disasters and accidents is shifting from television to online information (social media).
Social media such as Twitter have become important media to disseminate information immediately after a disaster or accident occurs.
However, it is difficult by hand to constantly watch the overflowing information and extract useful information from it.
Specti has the ability to detect things related to natural disasters and accidents from information flowing through social media such as Twitter, Instagram and Facebook, analyze the contents, determine whether the information is true or not, and then distribute it to users.
"We position a wide range of negative impact events that suspend or stagnate social activities as "crisis" (Murakami Kenjiro, CEO), and it is a crisis management support service that visualizes various crises occurring both in Japan and abroad.
NHK at the time of the Kumamoto earthquake that struck in April 2016 was the first major use case of Specti, and since then the trend of recruitment has spread rapidly among companies.
In addition to the press such as TV stations and newspapers, more than 350 companies in Japan, including companies that support social infrastructure such as electricity, gas and transportation, as well as local governments all over the country, are currently using Specti.
Analyze posts to determine the type of "crisis" and where it occurs
Specti distributes information through four steps: "collecting information", "analysis and content classification", "titleing", and "judging authenticity".
Companies must designate in advance the areas where information will be collected (prefectures, municipalities, etc.) and crisis categories (disasters, accidents, etc.).
Specti collects posts that correspond to that designation using the APIs provided by social media.
Next, the text, images and videos contained in the collected posts will be analyzed and classified.
For example, if there is a video of a fire truck, black smoke rising from the building, and orange flames coming out of the room, it will be classified as "fire".
In addition, images of overturned cars are classified as "traffic accidents", while images of water-covered roads are classified as "road floods".
Specti also estimates where disasters and accidents occur.
"We often don't know the location from posts, so we make an estimate by combining various information," said CEO Murakami.
For example, if a road sign or signboard is reflected in an image or video, information on the place name will be extracted from it, and the location will be identified by comparing it with the place name database.
